President Obama signed the HIV Organ Policy Equity (HOPE) Act into law, allowing scientists to conduct research on organ donations from individuals with HIV to other HIV-positive individuals. Previously, these transplants and studies on their safety and effectiveness were illegal. However, with advancements in HIV understanding and treatment, the prohibition became outdated. The HOPE Act lifts the research ban, potentially leading to life-saving organ donations for people with HIV while ensuring the safety of the transplant process and strengthening the national organ supply. This legislation aligns with President Obama's National HIV/AIDS Strategy, which aims to improve care for individuals living with HIV. The President expresses gratitude to Congress for their action in passing the HOPE Act.